Oct 20 2005	great place to stay	We've just returned from almost 2 weeks in London, during which we stayed at the Tria hotel.First of all, we enjoyed our stay and the hotel was perfectly ok!We've booked the room on the internet, via [...] - where you pay only a small amount to secure your booking, and the rest is paid directly in the hotel. Also, the price in this site was quite small - only 42.73 pounds a day (for 2 people + continental breakfast).It is a small hotel, located on a very quiet street and overlooking a small park.It is 5 minutes by foot from the nearest tube (Westbourne Park station), and you can get to a station with better choice of tube lines by bus just outside the hotel (every 5 minutes, a 5 minutes bus ride to Notting Hill Gate station).It is also in a walking distance from Paddington train station.The hotel overall is very clean, and it's a non-smoking hotel, which was very fine with us.The only place where smoking is allowed is in the lobby.In the lobby, there is a soft-drinks machine, a place to sit (sofas, TV and such), internet (0.5 pound for 0.5 hour), and a place where you can prepare tea and coffee (for free).There is also a safe deposit box that cost us only 3 (or 5???????????) pounds for all our stay.The room: of course it wasn't big, but for 2 persons it was fine. There are nice claret-colored carpets on the floor, and the mattresses have just been replaced with new ones (it happened during our stay). A mirror has also been added above the desk (although still a lamp lacks above it to turn it to a dressing table).I think the total room (including the en-suite shower) was around 3x5 meters.In the room there were: a double bed, a big wardrobe with mirrors as doors, a small writing desk (2 drawers and a bigger compartment) with a small lamp, a chair, a &quot;trouser press&quot; (a strange machine that presses and heats trousers - to replace ironing; didn't venture to use this thing, though), a TV set+remote, a telephone (we didn't try to call from it, but we did receive a call), and 2 glasses.There was no tea/coffee tray in the room.There is no air conditioning, which can be a problem in the summer. There is a small air-opening in the window (which can be closed), and it was enough for ventilation, most of the time of our stay.The shower looks pretty new and nice, there is also a toilet, and a washing basin (with one tap and hot-cold water mixer, and not 2 taps as it is in many places in England).In the shower: 2 big towels, 2 towel pegs, a feet towel, soap, hairdryer, a place to plug a shaver in. No hand towels, no shampoo.There was continental breakfast included, consisting of (and only): a small glass of orange juice, tea/coffee, milk, a bowl of cornflakes, 2 toasts, jam, butter. We did occasionally ask and get more toasts. Overall it was enough for us for a light breakfast.There wasn't any alteration in the food, except one-time different type of cornflakes.On the whole, the food wasn't anything incredible, but it was all fresh and I'd say usual.The breakfast room is in the basement but it has windows, and doesn't look dark at all.Tips:Remember to bring the special electricity plug for the UK sockets.It was very convenient and very worthy to buy unlimited 7-days oyster travelcard, which allows you to travel unlimited in selected zones of the tube and also on the buses. see http://www.tfl.gov.uk/tfl for more details.	
Jun 13 2005	Not too bad if you're on a budget	My 14 year old daughter and I stayed there as part of a package with Go-Today travel, and it was our first visit to London. The rooms don't have and thermostats in the room, so it was a bit chilly in the room, but the staff gave us a portable heater which warmed up the room just fine (the room is quite small). We had arrived 4 hours earlier than our check in time, but the staff was able to get us into a cleaned room within an hour. The breakfasts were included, but nothing spectacular....toast, jam, corn flakes, and tea or coffee. The closest metro is about 5 blocks away, but we felt completely safe walking back to the hotel late at night. It was quite a distance from most of the landmarks we wanted to see, but if you don't mind the subways, most things are just one or two trains aways since Paddington Station is only 2 stops from the subway near the hotel. The only 2 things that were problematic were that our shower hose had a hole in it, which made the water pressure pretty poor, and one day, our hotel door wouldn't open and the maintenance man had to come up and literally take the door off to fix the electronic lock. If you're looking for a hotel as somewhere to sleep while you enjoy the sights of London, this one is perfect, but if you want something even remotely luxurious, this is not the hotel for you. Personally, we were there to see London, not the inside of a hotel room.	
Mar 1 2005	Great location	Just got back from a week in London where I stayed at the Tria. I had a single room, small but adequate. The twelve-foot ceilings made the room seem larger. The small bathroom had all new fixtures. The heating system worked really well--not chilly like some London hotels in winter. I loved the quiet street (Even though I was on the front facing the street, I never heard any street noise.) The walls were very thick, so I heard little from the rooms above or next to me. The best feature was the location. Across the street were bus stops for buses to Notting Hill Gate--where I transferred to the Tube or to other bus routes. The Westbourne Park tube station was a few blocks walk, as was the Portobello Road market. I didn't really care for the breakfast that was offered--very basic, just corn flakes, toast, orange juice, coffee and tea. Some fresh fruit would have made me happy. I skipped the breakfast after the first couple of days and found cozy cafes near-by that offered homemade scones, etc. A good choice for the budget traveller--for me the money saved meant buying more books to lug home...	
