Jul 19 2004	Good budget hotel	The Tria is a good hotel for the budget conscious, especially in very pricey London. International clientele all ages. No frills here. Cost £65 a night for a twin room, less if booked on a website like London.Net. Small room, with cable TV and remote, telephone, and coffee/tea making equipment. Think basic dorm room. On the plus side: Clean, comfortable bed and pillows, remodeled bathrooms with great shower, all rooms nonsmoking (a rarity in London), internet access in lobby (£1 per 30 minutes), quiet street location with little noise within hotel except sound of water pipes in walls, fridge in lobby stocked with drinks for sale. Negatives: although hotel is generally nonsmoking, smoking is allowed on one side of the small lobby. If you have a room on the ground floor, smoke smell can drift under door. We paid by credit card which converted bill to $ at a higher than current exchange rate. Reception said there was nothing they could do about it--that the machine did it automatically. No time to discuss this as we were rushing to catch a train. But since the British also use this hotel, assume that they can charge in £s too. They arranged a cab to take us to train station but it turned out to be a private cab with no meter and a set rate of £7 to Paddington. Rate okay but don't know about liability issues and such. Not a lot of restaurants in immediate neighborhood but what's there were good. You can walk a few long blocks to busy streets to have more choices. All in all would probably stay there again. Especially if exchange rate stays high.	
